{"/service/ndnp/oru/batch_oru_longspur_ver01/data/sn88086023/0020219462A/1908022801/1092.xml":{"full_text":"PAGE EIGHT.\nDAILY EAST OREUtWIAN, PENRLKTO. OHKGON. FRIDAY, FEHHUAHY 28, 1W8.\nEIGHT PAGK&\nMarketing Becomes a Pleasure\nJ When you can do it in a store where\ncleanliness, convenience and .comfort, are\ndistinct features. You'll find these things\nfully embraced in our store.\nJ Added to this the superlative quality of\nour groceries and provisions, our generous\nmethods and our prompt and efficient de\nlivery system and you have the chief ele\nments of our trade-winning combination.\nStandard Grocery Co.\n\"The Best Groceries\"\nPLEASING\nnet\nPRESBYTERIAN GOObFELLOW\nS1UP CLUB SOCIAL MEETING\nForty Men Gotlier to Enjoy Feast ami\nHoar Splomllil rrogram of After\nDinner Talk. Special Mutdo by\nMale Quartette of the Oul Or\nganization Branch of National\nBrother IhxxI Ami Is for the Aid of\nGetieral Cliurch Work.\nAt the Presbyterian church last\nnight the Good Fellowship- club ot\nthat church gave a banquet that\nproved very pleasant and successful.\nDr. W. H. Bleakney, president of the\nPendleton academy, served as toast\nmaster and some' good responses were\nmade. One of the most enjoyable\nresponses was that by Attorney John\nMcCourt, who spoke upon the church\nfrom an outsider's standpoint Oth\ners who responded to toasts were\nProf. F. K. Noordhof, \"Object of the\nOrganization;\" C E. Fisher, 'Pen\ndleton's Prospects;\" W. I Van Nuys,\n\"Good Fellowship;\" and Douglas\nJohnson, \"Why We Should Not\nHelp.\" Music numbers were fur\nnished by the male quartette of the\nclub.\nthe banquet last night was the first\nCOLDS\nThe very hour a cold starts is the\ntime to check it. Don't wait It may\nbecome deep-seated and the cure will\nbe harder then. Eve.-y hour lost at\nthe start may add days to your suf\nfering. Take\nF S\nCold Capsules\nUsed In time they save all that\nmight follow sickness, worry.\npenses. They never fall.\nTallman Co.\nLeading Druggists.\none given by the club and Its success\nwas very pleasing to those behind\nthe movement, Abou,t 40 guests were\npresent The Ladies' Aid society\nserved the banquet in a most de\nlightful manner.\nThe Good Fellowship club Is an or\nganlzation of the men of the congre\ngation to promote a spirit of friend\nship and fellowship among the mem\nbers of the church and congregation\nand to assist in the various phases\nof the church work. The organiza\ntion is founded on the general prin\nciples of the National Brotherhood of\nthe Presbyterian church, which has\nthousands of men enrolled. The na\ntional organization was formed some\nthree or four years ago and has had\na remarkable growth. The various\nlocal organizations are allowed to\ntake whatever name they choose, but\nare all formed on the lines suggested\nby the national organization.\nBAKER CITY'S DILEMMA.\nGovernment Building Site Has Caused\nInternal Warfare Which Troubles\nCitizens.\nThat all is not peace In Baker Clif\nconcerning the government building\nsite and the location of the federal\ndistrict headquarters is shown by the\nfollowing Washington item, giving an\naccount of Mayor John's visit to the\nnational capital In the interests of\nBaker City. The dispatch says;\nC. A. Johns of Baker City, is en\ndeavoring to get work started on the\nBaker City public building. The\ngovernment owns the site and con\ngress has made appropriation for the\nbuilding, when certain Baker City\nmen made a kick and wanted the site\nchanged.\nBecause of their protest, prepare\ntlon of plans was suspended and\nnothing further was done by the de\npartment Mr. Johns says the objec\ntion to the site is not sufficiently se\nrious to Justify further delay He\nwants Immediate action.\nMrs. Froltt's Recital Postponed.\nThe recital which was to have been\ngiven by Mrs. W. C. E. Prultt on\nnext Monday evening, has been post\nponed, owing to Mrs. Selkirk-Norton's\nrecital at the Wm. Matlock home on\nthat evening.\n\"Helen\" Ives, a pretty telephone\neirl employed for the past three\nmonths In the Forest Exchange of the\nEell Telephone company at St. Louis,\nhas been fired because the company\naccidentally discovered that \"Helen\"\nwas a clever young man In disguise.\nI Do You Gel Your Portion ot the Cream 7\nAre you absolutely certain that your milk is free from\ndirt or infection and that it is handled in a clean, sanitary\nmanner? The only way to procure good rich, clean milk\nnot that with the cream poured off is to get milk in\nbottles.\nThat is the Kind We SeU;\nPendleton Creamery Co.\nPhone Main 155\nSEP SUNK\nSE\n0\nCMAJIIJLA COUNTY CREW\nTO CKOOK COUNTY\nFive Mtw leave for Maddy Station to\nSltrar Tltorouglibred Herds for\nlrlneviBt Company After Shear\ning lfl0 Rams a Henfl of 9000\nEwe WW He Tagged Slioarlii\nWill Continue from Now Until End\nof Season.\nThe sheepshearlng season in east\nern Oregon will be opened In earnest\non next Monday morning at the sheep\nranches of the Prlnevllle Land and\nLivestock company at Muddy Station\nIn Crook county, when a crew of\nUmatilla county shearers will begin\nshearing and tagging the thorough\nbred herds of that company.\nThe crew which has secured this\ncontract and which will leave tonight\nfor Crook county Is composed of\nJesse Lleuallen, John Rldenous,\nJames Harris of Weston, John Stan\nton of Athena and Ira Bugnes or this\ncity. They will shear 1600 rams for\nthis company and when that work is\ncompleted they will tag 9000 thor\noughbred ewes, after which they will\nreturn to Gilliam county to begin the\nspring shearing.\nThey will receive 25 cents per head\nfor shearing the rams and will be\npaid 15 per day for tagging the ewes.\nIt will require about three weeks to\ncomplete this work and by that tlm\nthe regular shearing season will open\nin eastern Oregon.\nNEARLY 2000 REGISTERED.\nIndications Point to Greater Total\nRcglsu-aUoti Than Two Years Ago.\nNearly 2000 voters have now regis\ntered for the coming primaries and\nelection and in view of the fact that\nan entire month still remains for reg\nistration there is every Indication that\nthe total this time will be greater than\nIt was two years ago.\nUnder the law registration must\nclose 14 days before the primaries are\nheld, April 17, and so they will be\nclosed on the evening of April 1.\nRegistration will be resumed after\nthe primaries.\nCandidates desiring to run for\ncounty offices must file their nomi\ninnling petitions by April 1, while\nthose running for state and district\noffices are required to have their pe\ntitions with the secretary of state 20\ndays before the primaries are held.\nNEW MINISTER, COMING.\nRev. Andrew Meldrom of Lexington,\nKy., Coming to Be Pastor of Clirl.\ntlun Church.\nA message received last evening by\nW. F. Taylor brought the Information\nthat Rev. Andrew Meldrom of Lex\nington, Ky., has accepted the call of\nthe First Christian church -of this\nc'ty to become Its pastor and that he\nwill arrive here to begin his work on\nMarch 15.\nRev, Meldrum has Just completed a\ntour of the wortd and Is a highly ca\npable man of excellent education. He\nhas preached In Australia and other\nforeign lands and comes well quali\nfied to glve excellent service to the\nchurch In this city. The congregation\nIs pleased to have secured a pastor\nafter many weeks of effort. The pul\np!t has been vacant since the depar\nture of Rev. Lee Ferguson several\nmonths ago and- active work will be\nresumed on the arrival of Rev. Meldrom.\nCondensed Report of Condition\nRendered\nComptroller of the Currency\nFebruary 14, 1908.\nCommercial National Bank\nUNITED STATES DEPOSITORY.\nRESOURCES.\nUNITED STATES BONDS $10-1,955.81\nLOANS AND DISCOUNTS 137,000.18\nWARRANTS 1,170.05\nREAL ESTATE 50000\nFURNITURE AND FIXTURES ..-7.053.48\nCASH ON HAND AND IN BANKS .01,541.21\n$313,123.73\nLIABILITIES.\nCAPITAL STOCK $.50,000.00\nSURPLUS AND UNDIVIDED PROFITS ...7,004.30\nNATIONAL RANK NOTES OUTSTANDING 48,700.00\nDEPOSITS 27'4\"-37\n$313,123.73\nX. P. OFFICIALS HERE.\nRe. Force, Cutler and Sauroll of the\nPnneo Division Ixxk Over the System.\nSuperintendent J. L. De Force, As\nsistant Superintendent J. G. Cutler\nand Charles Caurlol, roadmastes of\nthe Pasco division of the orthern\nPacific, were In the city last evening\nlooking over the system in th!s city\nand discussing contemplated Improve\nments. They are well pleased wltn\nthe business outlook of Umatilla\ncounty find expect a heavy movement\nof freight this\" spring in all parts of\nthe northwest.\nSuperintendent De Force has Just\nreturned from a visit In California,\nand was accompanied by h's family\nto this city.\nORDERED SHEARING MACHINE.\nEcho SheepnMMi Will Shear on a\nIinrpro Seale. Willi Improved Ma\nchines Tills Year.\nJoseph Cunha and R. N. Stanfleld\nhave Just ordered a sheep shearing\nmachine to cost about $1100 with a\ndally capacity of 2000 head of sheep.\nThey expect to shear at least 100,\n000 sheep during the season and have\nordered a latest model machine.\nRemains to Walla Walla.\nThe -remains of W. G. Whitney,\nwho was shot and killed near Wclser\nn fpw fi:ivs aeo were taken througn\nInst evenlnsr to Walla Walla for In\nterment. The murdered man was a\nbrother of W. C. Whitney, fruit In\nspcc'or of Walla Walla county, and\nwas well known In the Garden city.\nOrchestra to Umatilla.\nJohnson's orchestra left this after\nnoon for Umatilla, where It will fur\nnish music for a dance this evening\nJoseph Harper and daughter Edna\nwho have been vlsltinft at 'the resi\ndence of Mr. Harper's niece, Mrs. A.\nT. Thorouirhman. 208 North FoUrtn\nptreot, went to Pendleton yesterday\nafternoon for a short visit with rela\ntives. They will return the first of\nrpi wpek to reside on a farm wh ch\nMr. Harper recently purchased near\nCollege place. vvana waiia union\nlfMlWVtv item nfVpliM\nCrrMADS im New York Cirv\nWCethethatKpJLPMen'ikl4ri&,'\nht Clothes that KEEP Men'kucg\"\nCLOTHIERS TO THE\n0\nWe are making oiir\nInitial showing of\nlege Skald Clothes\nfor Young Men.\nThe collection is extensive and most represent-'\native, containing the popular patterns in more\nvaried and attractive models and styles than ever.\nIncluded in this line are to be found extreme and\nconservative styles in\nSPRING CLOTHING\nwhich are not shown elsewhere in the city.\nFor advance showing in hew spring clothing styles, see\nROOSEVELT'S i\n3ktt\nStore\nWhere You Trade to Save\nRUSSIAN FOLLOWS FLEET.\nStudies American MetlioilB an Battle\nships Make Long wuise\nHorn.\na Tj.aicin. naval officer, Com\nmander Alexis Dlatchkoff, is follow\ning the American battleship fleet\naround the .Horn. Probably he\nwishes to observe for himself the\nmnrmer In which the fleet stands the\ncruise and particularly now ine ma\n,i.. UohAves. No objection to his\nJourney -of observation appears to be\nfelt by the navy department, i\nBuffalo Express.\nTt, last sreat fleet voyage over a\nlong distance was that taken by Ro\nJestvensky's fleet. The public knows\nthat it revealed deficiencies in many\nunexpected quarters. So It Is not sur\nprising that a Russian orncer mioum\nbe studying our method of doing\nthings. Moreover, Russia Is nuilding\na new fleet, and Information regard\ning hfi nractlcal efficiency of various\nbattleship types Is valuable to her.\nWill rreach at Artnms.\nRev. Levi Johnson, Presbyterian\nSunday school missionary, will\nnh at Adams, morning and\nevening, next Sunday. All are cor\ndlally Invited to the services.\n4. Homo cooking at the\nAlexander Grocery Store\nSaturday, February 29.\nBy ladles of the\nChristian Church.\nOREGON'S\nOPPORTUNITY\nColonist Rates from all parts of the United States and Can\nada to all parts of Oregon and the Northwest will be again put Into\neffect by\nTHE OREGON RAILROAD NAVIGATION COMPANY and tlw\nSOUTHERN PACIFIC COMPANY.\n(Lines in Oregon.)\nMarch 1, 1908,\nand will continue dally throughout March and April. From the\nprincipal cities of the Middle West the rates will be as fallow\nFROM ll\"JU\nKA